‘It was so they could play quicker, because I didn’t want them on the course for six-and-a-half hours, as they were at Medinah,’ he argued.

Both captains are acutely aware that a lot of players are coming into this contest on the back of a heavy workload of eight tournaments in 10 weeks.

Indeed, American captain Tom Watson said he was concerned that a lot of his players are tired, which seemed a bizarre thing to flag up before the Ryder Cup had even started.  

